By allowing the extruder stepper motor to swivel, the bowden PFTE tube can be drastically shortened.  
I started by mounting the extruder outside the case of my Davinci 1.0, but the bowden cable was too long and I was having oozing issues.  I tried mounting the stepper inside the case, and I could shorten the bowden cable a little, but I still had to leave extra room so it would not kink while printing.  Finally, with this swivel fixture, I was able to significantly reduce the length of the bowden cable.  
I drilled a hole in the sheetmetal and used an M5 bolt, two washers, and a nut to hold a 608ZZ bearing in place.  This fixture fits on top of the bearing.

A treaded artillery piece suitable for sci-fi miniature wargaming.

The model is assembled into two parts.  The base, which consists of the treads and the lower chassis and the cannon which is pretty much everything else.  
Each tread is printed in two "halves" which should be glued together, and then each tread has a slot which the chassis fits.  
The cannon is six pieces. The upper chassis is the circular piece with the large peg that fits into the lower chassis, allowing the cannon some range of motion left and right. The center part of the cannon (with the triangular base) is glued directly to the lower chassis.   
The barrel is glued to the front (the side without the square peg) while the two back sections fit over the peg. First the cannon cover piece, then the back breach piece to fully hide the peg.  The sensor part should be glued into the impression on the top of the cannon, between two halves of the cover piece.

Ghostbuster's PKE Meter

I made this toy based on the shoe polisher that was used in the movie. It is for my great nephew, who is now a 7 year old full-time ghostbuster.
It is still a work in progress. I added quit a few pictures to show how I did the electronics, but the scope here is just to make the case:
  • Print one of each file.
  • connect the bottom handle and bottom base with 7/8" aluminum angle; plastic is not strong enough here; glue and screw.
  • Consider drilling out the posts and replacing them with 1/4" brass rod (it's what I did because I was afraid the plastic wasn't strong enough after all the wiring.
  • I used epoxy glue throughout, and 'painted' each part with acetone to make sure nothing delaminated. 4-40 screws to hold the case together.
  • Electronics are intense, so plan well and use a strong servo. My cheap miniature servo really didn't have enough guts.
  • Allow about 30 hours for total completion, including electronics....
  • See downloads for video PKE.MP4

description.text:
This a non-bowden mount system to use E3D's cyclop/chimera extruders with the Rididbot.
It reused the original Rigidbot single-extruder alluminium plate and consists in a plate to receive the two original NEMA motors, and fixations to maintain the motor on the plate.
It uses the mount from Sactocal here http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:664341, including the risers, but I have remaid the belt riser to fit with my 20 teeth pulley.
The fan mount is also originally from Sactotal (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:709010), but I have shortned it to fit with the plate and it uses the main cone from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:310686.

I have printed all parts in ABS, 0.2mm and 100% infill for robustness. You have to make a really slight trimming on the middle of the aluminium plate (see picture) to fix the extruder to both the mount and the plate.
1- Attach the extuder to the Sactotal mount with the two front screws.
2- Screw the printed plate to the aluminium plate, together with the risers.
2- Screw the mount/extruder assembly to the plate
2- Screw the 2 motor fixations to the printed plate
3- Put the motors inplace and screw them to the printed plate
4- Screw the the endstop part to the endestop riser
5- Screw the fan mount You're done!

There are a number of advantages to using glass as the build plate on a 3D Printer.   Not having to worry about retaping and not having to buy expensive wide rolls of tape (or worry about tape lines on your print) are why I choose to use glass, or more recently FR-4, on my build platforms.   
A major downside of using glass or FR-4, however, is the loss of build space that can result from having the build plate secured with the traditional binder clips.   It is never a good thing to hear the noise your printer makes when the nozzle catches on one of those damn clips!  
This thing provides a way of securing glass or FR-4 without using a binder clip there-by preserving as much build space as possible...and...avoiding having a nozzle drag across a binder clip!

The clips that I used were "Newlec Edge Beam Clip. For 8mm - 12mm Grip, 10mm - 11mm diameter".  I am not sure if they are available outside the UK though.  If you are only planning to use FR-4 the clip size with a 4-7mm grip might be better though I have not tried it.  The larger grip required that the spacer have a tab to compensate for the FR-4 being thinner than glass.  
Print in ABS if you print in ABS as PLA will deform quickly at ABS bed temperatures!  Even the ABS inserts will deform over time so plan on replacing them once in a while.   I have ordered a set printed with Resin as I have been surprised how quickly my ABS prints are showing the signs of heat.  
The printed part is inserted into the metal cut down clip such that the curve of the printed part matches the curve of the clip.   On the FR-4 part this will then position the tongue on the printed part such that it will slip under the build platform forcing the metal clip to then exert pressure on the glass or FR-4.  Please see the photos.  
If you are planning on using this with FR-4 you might be able to get by with the clip one size smaller than the ones that I used.  This is strongly recommended.   Another alternative is to get the spaces printed in something with a higher melting point than ABS.  I have had them printed in resin (last picture in series) and will see how that works.  In the meantime I am going to order the smaller clips!

description.text: Your 3D you!

This is my first draft at a printable frame for a wheeled cart for a disabled puppy. Problems I'm running into:
  • I printed the draft in low quality, so I don't know how much of the structural problems have to do with the low quality, and how much is design flaw. (The rounded bar where the dog's legs can rest, connecting both halves of the cart are particularly flimsy.)
  • The framing is 1 cm in width, which will have to be widened at least where the wheel axles go, if not around the entire frame.
  • The cart is not adjustable, and is almost at the maximum size for printing. In order to make the frame work for the puppy as it grows larger, I will need to be able to create smaller, assemble-able parts to be printed individually.
I am designing using SketchUp. I am incorporating inline skate wheels, and for now I'm using a model dog, because the puppies who need the carts are at someone else's house.

description.text:
This is a model of an umbilic torus created in blender. An equilateral triangle was extruded, then each of the three sides were slightly pushed in by 50%. Finally, the entire extrusion was proportionally enlarged following a sine wave and then twisted in on itself to make a torus.  
The result is an umbilic torus that rotates a full 120 degrees through 2pi and grows and shrinks as it travels.
Only support from the platform is necessary for printing. There's a slight possibility this could be oriented to not require supports but I didn't investigate that idea.

This single channel 200kHz bandwidth 1 Ms/s oscilloscope is very simple, and is mostly meant as a learning tool. Which is fine, but I think it may even be quite useful as a simple field oscilloscope for many applications. I have therefore created this case which enables fully portable battery powered usage, which the original design did not provide for. description.text: As a kid I had a an air powered toy car. Yesterday I got the idea to try and design an air powered motor which can later be incorporated in all kinds of applications. I'm not going to explain the principle as the animated GIF in this link explains it perfectly: http://www.animatedengines.com/co2.shtml As I have only completed my design work today I haven't yet had a chance to print it and look for any flaws. Also for the sake of easily printing all the parts the design might be slightly over complicated. It is however fairly small (6.28cc capacity) and therefore all parts "should" print straight and square. One major feature of my design is that multiple motors can be daisy-chained to form a larger multi-cylinder motor. So far the only thing missing is a 3mm wrist-pin connecting the piston to the con-rod. As this is a work in progress I do not know what the clearances are and therefore how freely this will turn once assembled

Print the following to build one single-cylinder motor:
1 x valve cover.STL
1 x cylinder head.STL
1 x cylinder block.STL
1 x piston.STL
1 x piston valve pin.STL
1 x conrod.STL
2 x conrod - piston spacers.STL
2 x conrod - crank spacers.STL
2 x crank arms.STL
1 x crank big end journal.STL
2 x crank main journal.STL
1 x crank case.STL Extra parts required:
1 x soft compression spring (6mm o.d. x 12mm long) (I'm using one from an AA battery holder so it's 6mm dia on one end and 11mm dia on other end)
1 x 6mm plastic BB pellet
8 x M3 x 10mm screws
4 x M3 x 25mm screws
18-19mm x 3mm pin or filament
Some sort of bottle into which you can compress some air
Tubing connecting the air-bottle to the valve cover inlet. Assembly:
Clean up all holes. Top and bottom corner holes of cylinder block and 4 holes on top of cylinder head can be tapped to M3. Drop the BB pellet into the cylinder head and let it rest in the bottom hole. Insert the spring on top of it. Screw down the the valve cover on top of this assembly with 4 10mm screws. Screw the cylinder head assembly down onto the cylinder block with 4 10mm screws. Take one crank arm and install the big-end journal into the hole oppsite the hole with the raised edge and also on the opposite face ofthe crank arm (the journal must point away from raised edge). Slide a conrod crank spacer of the journal, then the conrod and then the other crank spacer. Install the other crank arm so that both arms are parallel and in the same direction and both raised edges on the outside of the assembly. Now install the 2 crank main journals into the holes with the raised edge. Install the piston onto the conrod might be a little trickier. Basically the two conrod piston spacers must be on either side of the conrod, the piston over them with the 3mm pin/filament through them to hold them together. This whole piston and crank assembly can be dropped into the cylinder blockfrom the bottom (piston first obviously) so that the two crank main journals rest in the notches in the bottom of the block. Now install the crank case of this and screw in place with the 25mm screws. Fill your air "reservoir" connect the tubing from it to the intake valve on top and give the motor a spin. If everything is just loose enough it will run on it own until the air supply is finished

This OpenSCAD script will generate a grid pattern of small cuboids attached to a large flat cuboid. The heights of the smaller cuboids will alternate sequentially.
The user can specify the number of rows & columns as well as the length & breadth of the smaller cuboids and the separation between adjacent cuboids.
The Number of different heights and the difference in height between smaller cuboids can be specified too.
The user can also choose whether or not to add Keyed connectors so that they can print multiple items that can then be easily connected together to for an arbitrarily large grid
The overall effect will be like the tread pattern of a mountain bike tyre or a 3D checker board.

title: ATX Power Supply Mount With Switch Mount

description.text: Picked up a nice ATX power supply for my 8" Prusa i3v but didn't want it just sitting on the workbench so I decided to make a mount for it, after I decided to modify the heck out of the power supply to remove the unnecessary cables. I designed a switch bracket to go with it that sits where the OEM spool holder did. I have included all the FreeCAD files so you can edit as necessary. I used a 4 position barrier strip for the power wires and set it up so I can design a cover later. I used M3 inserts in 2 of the mounting holes so the cover can be secured there later.

The power supply mount uses all M3 hardware, the corners are just tapped M3 since they are not really structural. The switch bracket uses M2 hardware due to it's smaller size. I drilled new holes in the wooden frame of the printer to mount everything and the wire tie downs are optional. All the mounting to the frame uses M3x16mm and nylon lock nuts.

title: Waterwheel
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is my design of a waterwheel which i am going to attach to water wheel house feature. I will post the rest of the design for that once they are complete. The wheel is design to work with two bearings and an m4 bolt with two nuts.  
Size: Diameter: 100mm, thickness: 30mm

Extra materials you need, all found on ebay:
2 x BEARING TYPE: 684 4x9x4mm
1 x M4 Bolt (min 35mm in length)
2 x M4 nuts I printed this with abs in two parts hence why i have put both the full and the divided files. I then glued them together with acetone. It actually printed very well and only had 2 small separations on two different paddles but they where quick to fix with acetone. I recommend that you print this with a brim of around 10 mm so you don't get any lift. The over all assembly is quite easy with one nut going into the closed off part and then a bearing over it, then just put the other bearing in the open part and run a m4 bolt thru them. The idea here is that the m4 bolt screws into the nut and then as the wheel turns the nut has no where to catch so it doesn't come undone. So to lock it in i recommend putting slight pressure on the m4 bolt to screw it in.
To unscrew it pull the m4 while unscrewing. Both tasks take about 15 seconds, in the end you still may feel it's lose but give it a try. The wheel has been spinning for 14 days non stop and so far it hasn't come off. If you turn the wheel upside down and spin it, eventually it comes off but it was designed to turn at 90 degrees. If you feel that it may come off you could possibly glue the nut to the m4 bolt just make sure you do it with both bearing in the m4, then you just need to push it into place.
